primary benchmarks for Asian markets, further exacerbated the pricing crisis, as refiners scrambled to secure alternative medium sour feedstocks.United States Gulf Coast Refining Architecture and the Heavy Sour DeficitThe precise chemical breakdowns illustrated in Table 1 dictate the operational reality of the United States Gulf Coast (USGC) refining complex. Geographically spanning from Corpus Christi, Texas, to Pascagoula, Mississippi, Petroleum Administration for Defense District 3 (PADD 3) represents the most complex and globally dominant refining hub on the planet.Paradoxically, while the United States is the world's largest producer of crude oil—generating record volumes of light, sweet crude from unconventional shale basins—the USGC refinery architecture is explicitly optimized for heavy, sour, and highly corrosive foreign crude. During the 1990s and early 2000s, global oil majors invested billions of dollars into deep-conversion infrastructure, adding massive delayed coking and fluid catalytic hydrocracking units to process cheap, dense feedstocks from Venezuela, Mexico, and the Middle East.Because heavy sour crudes trade at a substantial discount to light sweet benchmarks, the ability to chemically crack these heavy molecules into high-margin diesel and aviation fuels generates highly lucrative "coker crack spreads". Consequently, the USGC operates as a giant arbitrage engine, exporting domestic light sweet shale oil to Europe and Asia, while importing dense, sulfur-heavy barrels to maximize refinery utilization. The total operable atmospheric crude oil distillation capacity of the USGC refineries tailored specifically for these heavy sour inputs is approximately 7.5 to 7.6 million barrels per calendar day.Table 2 outlines the specific USGC refineries designed with deep conversion coking capacity for heavy sour crude processing, alongside their corporate owners and operating capacities as of 2026.Refinery LocationCorporate OwnerOperable Capacity (bbl/day)St